Bietsetal.2021-ColloqueLaPrhistoiresouslestropiques.json,"Engaging in community archaeology: a multidisciplinary approach for researchand conservation on the Unesco site of Sangiran, IndonesiaCorentin Biets (mnhn, Éveha International), Sih Natalia Sukmi (mnhn, uksw), Anne-Marie Sémah(mnhn), François Sémah (mnhn) The Sangiran siteOntheJavaIsland, Indonesia,Sangiranisa56km²boutonnière(Es,1931)makingitacrucialplacetostudy the about 1.5 My to 0.2 My (Matsu’ura et al., 2020; Sémah, 1984) southeast asianpalaeolandscapes (Sémah2014). Subject torapiderosion, fortuitous surfacefindings onthesitearelikely.In the early 1930's, cooperation with the local people soon began to give results regarding thelocalisation of fossil bearing layers. It continued through the20thcenturywithlocal peopletakingactivepart inresearch.Thelocals' tacitknowledgeofthefieldledtothediscoveryoftheSangiran17fossil by Towikromo andTukiminin1969. But duetoarewardingsystem, local interest for findingswas rather economic than scientific. However, this awareness constitutes a good embryo toovercome conservation issues.Its 235.563 dwellers makes it important to consider the interests of local people. A social andarchaeological science multidisciplinary approach was conducted to meet some of the Unesco'sOutstanding Universal Value framework. So, howto (re)formulate a multidisciplinary approach inarchaeology, and what to expect? MethodsTheHumanOriginsHeritageprogram(HOH)(since2018)andthePuCungTanahSubur/Wiji(PCTS/W)excavation(since2009)wereusedasexperimentalmomentsintheconstructionofacommunityandparticipatory archaeology program.HOH lasts about 10days everyyear inSangiranandSalatiga(JavaCentral). It gives theopportunityfor mixed students/locals teams to investigate scientific questions onthefield. Thesecanrelatetolocalmyths,hydrology,landscapes,prehistoricheritage,museums,etc.Eachteamundertakesseveralworkshops, co-constructing protocols in sociology, experimental archaeology, archaeological surveyor biology.ThePCTS/Wexcavationis afieldschool focusingonthecultureandenv (2020) https://doi.org/10.1126/science.aau8556."
