purnomo-et-al-2024-the-genetic-origins-and-impacts-of-historical-papuan-migrations-into-wallacea.json,"PNAS 2024 Vol. 121 No. 52 e2412355121 https://doi.org/10.1073/pnas.2412355121 1 of 10 RESEARCH ARTICLE | Significance We present a comprehensive study of the human genetic history of the Wallacean Archipelago and West Papuan regions of Indonesia, including 254 newly sequenced genomes, mostly from previously undocumented populations. In combination with linguistic and archaeological evidence, we show that Wallacean societies were transformed by the spread of genes and languages from West Papua in the past 3,500 y—the same period that Austronesian seafarers were actively mixing with Wallacean and Papuan groups. These migrant groups have largely replaced local Wallacean ancestry sources, challenging common assumptions that Papuan-related ancestry in Wallacea descends from first human migrants enroute to Sahul >50,000 y ago, and suggesting that these ancient movements may not be readily recoverable from modern genetic data alone. The authors declare no competing interest. This article is a PNAS Direct Submission. Copyright © 2024 the Author(s). Published by PNAS. This open access article is distributed under Creative Commons Attribution - NonCommercial- NoDerivatives License 4.0 (CC BY- NC- ND). 1To whom correspondence may be addressed. Email: gludhug.purnomo@adelaide.edu.au or ray.tobler@anu. edu.au. This article contains supporting information online at https://www.pnas.org/lookup/suppl/doi:10.1073/pnas. 2412355121/- /DCSupplemental. Published December 17, 2024. GENETICS The genetic origins and impacts of historical Papuan migrations into Wallacea Gludhug A. Purnomoa,b,c,1 , Shimona Kealyd,e , Sue O’Connord,e , Antoinette Schapperf,g, Ben Shawd,h, Bastien Llamasa,b,i,j , Joao C. Teixeiraa,b,h,k , Herawati Sudoyoc, and Raymond Toblera,d,h,1 Affiliations are included on p. 9. Edited by James O’Connell, The University of Utah, Salt Lake City, UT; received July 21, 2024; accepted October 30, 2024 The tropical archipelago of Wallacea was first settled by anatomically moder (2024) https://doi.org/10.1073/pnas.2412355121"
