DiangKaung_DiangBalu_Kalimantan_15000yrrockshelters.json,"Late Pleistocene to recent: Human activities in the deep interior equatorial rainforest of Kalimantan, Indonesian Borneo Vida P.R. Kusmartono a, b, *, Imam Hindarto b, Eko Herwanto b a School of Archaeology and Anthropology, AD Hope Building, Australian National University, Acton, ACT 2601, Australia b Balai Arkeologi Banjarmasin, Jalan Gotong Royong II, Rt. 06/09, Banjarbaru, Kalimantan Selatan 7071 1, Indonesia Keywords: Kalimantan Equatorial rainforest Pleistocene archaeology Holocene archaeology Kapuas River Radiocarbon dating abstract From the onset of archaeological research in Kalimantan (Indonesian Borneo) in 1939, there have been only 2 investigations within the deep interior equatorial rainforest of the island. These were at the sites of Nanga Balang and Diang Kaung, both in the upper Kapuas drainage basin in the geographical centre of Borneo. Both sites were dated to c. 3000 BP by the previous researchers. In this report, preliminary results of new excavations carried out at the rock-shelter complexes of Diang Kaung and Diang Balu are reported. AMS radiocarbon dating of 12 charcoal samples from the two sites indicates two main periods of human activity, one being 15 to 1 1 cal. ka, with a second spanning the recent past from 1500 to 150 BP. Taken together, these dates con ﬁrm the intermittent existence of human occupation of the deep interior equatorial rainforest of Borneo through at least 15,000 years. © 2016 Elsevier Ltd and INQUA. All rights reserved. 1. Introduction Despite previous arguments to the contrary ( Bailey et al., 1989), a variety of ethnographic, ecological, and archaeological evidence has now demonstrated the ability of our species to inhabit inland rainforest environments far from coastlines without access to other resources ( Barton et al., 2012 ). For example, Townsend's (1990) study on the Saniyo-Hiyowe (Upper Sepik River, Papua New Guinea) indicated that these people could exploit wild sago ( Met- roxylon) as the main carbohydrate s (2016) https://doi.org/10.1016/j.quaint.2016.09.025"
