Pleistocene_Sangiran_Java.json,"New taphonomical approaches: The Javanese Pleistocene open-air sites (Sangiran, central Java) Anne Bouteaux *, Anne-Marie Moigne De´partement de pre´histoire, Muse´um national d’Histoire naturelle, 1 rue Rene´ Panhard, 75013 Paris, France article info Article history: Available online 30 October 2009 abstract Since the 1960s, the National Indonesian Center for Archaeological Research, in collaboration with the Gajah Mada University, has been organizing ﬁeld excavations on open-air sites in the Sangiran dome, one of the most famous places of palaeoanthropological discoveries in Southeast Asia. That project led to the discovery of Homo erectus fossils, and the collection of numerous mammal fossils in localities such as Tanjung, Sendang Busik, Ngrejeng Plupuh, Grogol Plupuh, and Bukuran. During the 1990s, a French– Indonesian team excavated the Ngebung 2 locality. Most of the bone assemblages from these sites come from the volcanic–sedimentary Kabuh layers (Middle Pleistocene) deposited in a ﬂuvial context. The best-represented mammal species are large bovids and smaller cervids. The taphonomical study of the collections is the ﬁrst carried out on Javanese sites. The degree of fragmentation is high. The teeth and the extremities prevail in most of sites. Water action, either chemical or mechanical, is predominant in the origin and the modiﬁcation of the assemblages. Carnivores are almost absent in the material and the traces of their actions are rare. Anthropic inﬂuence is obvious at Ngebung 2, according to archeozoo- logical studies, correlated to the occurrence of lithic artefacts. /C2112009 Elsevier Ltd and INQUA. All rights reserved. 1. Introduction Homo erectus is the ﬁrst species of the genus Homo that can be found outside Africa. Remains of this hominid have been recov- ered in Africa and Asia dated between 1.8 and 0.3 Ma. This widespread geographical distribution proves that Homo erectus was able to migrate to various places in the world. The Indone- sian archi (2009) https://doi.org/10.1016/j.quaint.2009.10.007"
