GuaMapkan_Alor.json,"Quaternary International 603 (2021) 125–138 Available online 28 October 2020 1040-6182/© 2020 Elsevier Ltd and INQUA. All rights reserved. Burial practices in the early mid-Holocene of the Wallacean Islands: A sub-adult burial from Gua Makpan, Alor Island, Indonesia Sofia C. Samper Carro a , b , c , * , Tahlia J. Stewart a , Mahirta d , Rachel Wood a , e , Sue O ’ Connor b , f a School of Archaeology and Anthropology, College of Arts and Social Sciences, Australian National University, Canberra, ACT, Australia b Archaeology and Natural History, College of Asia and the Pacific, Australian National University, Canberra, ACT, Australia c Centre d ’ Estudis del Patrimoni Arqueologic, Facultat de Lletres, Universitat Autonoma de Barcelona, Bellaterra, Spain d Departemen Arkeologi, Fakultas Ilmu Budaya, Universitas Gadjah Mada, Yogyakarta, Indonesia e Research School of Earth Sciences, Australian National University, Canberra, ACT, Australia f ARC Centre of Excellence for Australian Biodiversity and Heritage, Australian National University, Canberra, ACT, Australia ARTICLE INFO Keywords: Wallacea Alor island Early holocene Human remains Burial practices Mortuary analysis ABSTRACT Mortuary contexts in geographical and chronological settings such as islands are key to investigating human migration pathways, population replacements, diet, health, occupational activities, belief systems as well as other aspects of social behaviour. Located between Mainland Southeast Asia and the Pacific, Island Southeast Asia is of particular interest in this respect. As yet, however, few complete burials predating the Neolithic have been recovered and described from within this vast region. This paper presents a sub-adult burial from Gua Makpan, Alor Island, Indonesia, which is dated to the early mid-Holocene. The anatomical description and bioskeletal profile of the remains is complemented by the analysis of mortuary practices. Our results suggest a delayed primary burial or a secondary tre (2021) https://doi.org/10.1016/j.quaint.2020.10.004"
