localityInfoPDFLaili_Cave.json,"ROAD Summary Data Sheet for locality Laili Cave The project ""The Role of Culture in Early Expansions of Humans"" (ROCEEH) is administered by the Heidelberg Academy of Sciences and Humanities. It has been promoted by the Joint Science Conference of the Federal Government and the governments of the states of the Federal Republic of Germany in the Academies' Programme. Funding is provided by the Federal Government of Germany (Federal Ministry of Education, Science and Research) and the states of Baden-Wurttemberg (Ministry of Science, Research and the Arts) and Hesse (Ministry of Science and the Arts). Provided by ROCEEH 2025 under CC BY-SA 4.0 (2025) https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pone.0289513"
West EurasianGenetics.json,"Western Eurasian genetic in ﬂuences in the Indonesian archipelago Pradiptajati Kusuma a, b, Murray P. Cox c, Nicolas Brucato a, d, Herawati Sudoyo b, Thierry Letellier a, François-Xavier Ricaut a, * a Laboratoire d'Anthropologie Mol /C19eculaire et Imag /C19erie de Synth /C18ese UMR-5288, Universit /C19e de Toulouse, Toulouse, France b Genome Diversity and Diseases Laboratory, Eijkman Institute for Molecular Biology, Jakarta, Indonesia c Statistics and Bioinformatics Group, Institute of Fundamental Sciences, Massey University, Palmerston North, New Zealand d Center for Linguistics, University of Leiden, Leiden, The Netherlands article info Article history: Available online 18 August 2015 Keywords: Western Eurasia India Arabia Indonesia Mitochondrial DNA Y chromosome abstract Western Eurasia, notably the Near East and South Asia (Indian sub-continent), has interacted with Indonesia through Indian Ocean trade (the Maritime Silk Route) for more than 2000 years. The Indi- anization, and later Islamization, of Indonesia was enacted largely through trading activities, but also spread with help from the many Indianized and Islamic kingdoms that reigned over parts of the Indo- nesian archipelago during this time. Western Eurasian interaction left behind not only imported trade goods and cultural features, but also genetic traces. To locate the primary areas of Western Eurasian genetic in ﬂuence in Indonesia, we have assembled published uniparental genetic data from ~2900 Indonesian individuals. Frequency distributions show that Western Eurasian paternal lineages are found more commonly than Western Eurasian maternal lineages. Furthermore, the origins of these paternal lineages are more diverse than the corresponding maternal lineages, predominantly tracing back to South West and South Asia, and the Indian sub-continent, respectively. Indianized kingdoms in the Indonesian archipelago likely played a major role in dispersing Western Eurasian lineages, as these kingdoms overla (2015) https://doi.org/10.1016/j.quaint.2015.06.048"
West EurasianGenetics.json,"Western Eurasian genetic in ﬂuences in the Indonesian archipelago Pradiptajati Kusuma a, b, Murray P. Cox c, Nicolas Brucato a, d, Herawati Sudoyo b, Thierry Letellier a, François-Xavier Ricaut a, * a Laboratoire d'Anthropologie Mol /C19eculaire et Imag /C19erie de Synth /C18ese UMR-5288, Universit /C19e de Toulouse, Toulouse, France b Genome Diversity and Diseases Laboratory, Eijkman Institute for Molecular Biology, Jakarta, Indonesia c Statistics and Bioinformatics Group, Institute of Fundamental Sciences, Massey University, Palmerston North, New Zealand d Center for Linguistics, University of Leiden, Leiden, The Netherlands article info Article history: Available online 18 August 2015 Keywords: Western Eurasia India Arabia Indonesia Mitochondrial DNA Y chromosome abstract Western Eurasia, notably the Near East and South Asia (Indian sub-continent), has interacted with Indonesia through Indian Ocean trade (the Maritime Silk Route) for more than 2000 years. The Indi- anization, and later Islamization, of Indonesia was enacted largely through trading activities, but also spread with help from the many Indianized and Islamic kingdoms that reigned over parts of the Indo- nesian archipelago during this time. Western Eurasian interaction left behind not only imported trade goods and cultural features, but also genetic traces. To locate the primary areas of Western Eurasian genetic in ﬂuence in Indonesia, we have assembled published uniparental genetic data from ~2900 Indonesian individuals. Frequency distributions show that Western Eurasian paternal lineages are found more commonly than Western Eurasian maternal lineages. Furthermore, the origins of these paternal lineages are more diverse than the corresponding maternal lineages, predominantly tracing back to South West and South Asia, and the Indian sub-continent, respectively. Indianized kingdoms in the Indonesian archipelago likely played a major role in dispersing Western Eurasian lineages, as these kingdoms overla (2015) https://doi.org/10.1016/j.quaint.2015.06.048."
domesticate-dispersal-human-agency-and-connectivity-in-island-southeast-asia-during-the-holocene.json,"80 808080 THREE DOMESTICATE DISPERSAL, HUMAN AGENCY AND CONNECTIVITY IN ISLAND SOUTHEAST ASIA DURING THE HOLOCENE Tim Denham The idea of a ‘people without history’ is an old one. Although not always expressed in Wolf’s language, the notion that non- agricultural societies were relatively static, timeless and ‘outside’ history is ancient (Trigger 2006 ). Within Island Southeast Asia (ISEA), such concepts and notions of history have been reinforced by the farming- language dispersal hypothesis (Diamond and Bellwood 2003 ; Bellwood 2005 ), namely, the out- of- Taiwan model, and a related concept, the spread of the Island Southeast Asian Neolithic (Spriggs 2007 ). Arguably, these interpretations of macro- history have simplifi ed, as well as obviated the need to fully engage with, the Holocene history of ISEA. There are lingering perceptions that the advent of ‘full- on’ farming and Neolithic practices marked the beginning of ‘revolutionary change’, whereas pre- existing practices were not historically signifi cant (Spriggs 2010 ; cf. Donohue and Denham 2010 ). Here, I argue that the farming- language dispersal hypothesis for ISEA, also known as the Austronesian dispersal hypothesis, is a ‘palaeo- colonial’ template that has, in eff ect, negated the historical effi cacy of the people who inhabited ISEA before, as well as during Austronesian language dispersal and the spread of Taiwanese material cultural infl uences. Fundamentally, the purpose of the chapter is to refl ect upon the ways subjects are formed within archaeological discourses about the distant past, with specifi c reference to ISEA during the Holocene. In contrast to recurrent portrayals, ISEA, either separately or taken together with the New Guinea region (ISEA- NG), was not a relatively benign https://doi.org/10.1017/9781108573276.005 Published online by Cambridge University Press (2010) https://doi.org/10.1017/9781108573276.005"
