Archaeology in Oceania - 2022 - Perston - Stone‐flaking technology at Leang Bulu Bettue  South Sulawesi  Indonesia.json,"Archaeology in Oceania, V ol. 57 (2022): 249–272 DOI: 10.1002/arco.5272 Stone-ﬂaking technology at Leang Bulu Bettue, South Sulawesi, Indonesia Yinika L. Perston, Mark W . Moore, n.f.n. Suryatman, Basran Burhan, Budianto Hakim, n.f.n. Hasliana, Adhi Agus Oktaviana, Rustan Lebe, Irfan Mahmud and Adam Brumm YLP , MWM, nS, BB, AB:Australian Research Centre for Human Evolution, Grifﬁth University; MWM: Department of Archaeology and Palaeoanthropology, University of New England; nH: nfnS: Department of Archaeology, Faculty of Cultural Sciences, Hasanuddin University; BH, IM: nfnS: Pusat Riset Arkeologi Prasejarah dan Sejarah, Badan Riset Inovasi Nasional; AAO: Badan Riset Inovasi Nasional; AAO: Place, Evolution and Rock Art Heritage Unit, Grifﬁth University; RL: Balai Pelestarian Cagar Budaya ABSTRACT Approximately 50000 stone artefacts have been recovered from the prehistoric site of Leang Bulu Bettue (LBB), on the W allacean island of Sulawesi, in Indonesia. This large assemblage offers the opportunity to produce a large-scale, comprehensive model of the early lithic technologies of South Sulawesi. Through the analysis of half of this assemblage, this study identiﬁes a technological shift between the artefacts produced ca.50–40 thousand years ago (ka) – the “Lower Industry” – and the “Upper Industry” artefacts produced ca.40–16 ka. The majority of the assemblage belongs to the Upper Industry, and these artefacts are associated with portable art, ornamentation, and the Homo sapiens remains reported in previous works. These Upper Industry artefacts are largely made on chert that was brought to the site, sometimes in the form of large ﬂake blanks, which was further reduced within the cave and used for ochre and plant processing. Artefact reduction was strategic during this period, and the bipolar method was frequently used for controlled reduction of ﬂakes of various sizes. This represents a shift from the technology seen on the small number of Lower Industry artefacts, r (2022) https://doi.org/10.1002/arco.5272"
