age_of_the_djetis_beds_in_east_and_central_java.json,"ANTIQUITY artifacts move downwards when the sand in which they are caught is alternatively wetted and allowed to dry. These movements vary from piece to piece but seem to be in proportion to the depth. Distinct archaeological horizons probably exis- ted at Gombe Point, but they have been disturbed. The Kalinian is probably to be considered as a concentration of one or more industries on the bedrock. The Kalinian is partially mixed with Djokocian in its upper levels. The Djokocian itself is contaminated by the Ndolian. It has now become clear that the archaeological units do not represent homogeneous industries. Consequently the typo- logical definition of these units and their chrono- logical interrelationship do not make sense. An optimistic view would allow one to say that the dates give an approximate estimate of the age of the various occupations at Gombe. A pessimistic view- point is that all that can be deduced from the dates is that men lived at Gombe from before 43,000 years onwards. The prehistory of the South-Western part of Central Africa (North Angola, KasaT, Kwango, Lower-Zayre) is based on the study either of surface collections or of sites located in an environ- ment similar to that of Gombe. We have evidence that some of these sites have been disturbed in the same way as Gombe and are afraid that this applies to most of them. This could be an explana- tion of the inconsistencies that at present prevail in the typology, chronology and nomenclature of the prehistoric industries of this region (Clark, 1971, 67-8). The new excavations at the Gombe Point yield an opportunity for the critical revision of these problems. On the other hand, they have revealed an interesting pottery that, whether neolithic or iron age, could perhaps be the earliest known in this part of Africa. BEQUAERT, M. 1938. Les fouilles derean Colette 2 Kalina, Ann. Mus. Congo Belge, SBrie I, T. I (Tervuren). CLARK, J. D. 1963. Prehistoric cultures of Northeast Angola and their signific https://doi.org/10.1017/S0003598X0010376X"
age_of_the_djetis_beds_in_east_and_central_java.json,"ANTIQUITY artifacts move downwards when the sand in which they are caught is alternatively wetted and allowed to dry. These movements vary from piece to piece but seem to be in proportion to the depth. Distinct archaeological horizons probably exis- ted at Gombe Point, but they have been disturbed. The Kalinian is probably to be considered as a concentration of one or more industries on the bedrock. The Kalinian is partially mixed with Djokocian in its upper levels. The Djokocian itself is contaminated by the Ndolian. It has now become clear that the archaeological units do not represent homogeneous industries. Consequently the typo- logical definition of these units and their chrono- logical interrelationship do not make sense. An optimistic view would allow one to say that the dates give an approximate estimate of the age of the various occupations at Gombe. A pessimistic view- point is that all that can be deduced from the dates is that men lived at Gombe from before 43,000 years onwards. The prehistory of the South-Western part of Central Africa (North Angola, KasaT, Kwango, Lower-Zayre) is based on the study either of surface collections or of sites located in an environ- ment similar to that of Gombe. We have evidence that some of these sites have been disturbed in the same way as Gombe and are afraid that this applies to most of them. This could be an explana- tion of the inconsistencies that at present prevail in the typology, chronology and nomenclature of the prehistoric industries of this region (Clark, 1971, 67-8). The new excavations at the Gombe Point yield an opportunity for the critical revision of these problems. On the other hand, they have revealed an interesting pottery that, whether neolithic or iron age, could perhaps be the earliest known in this part of Africa. BEQUAERT, M. 1938. Les fouilles derean Colette 2 Kalina, Ann. Mus. Congo Belge, SBrie I, T. I (Tervuren). CLARK, J. D. 1963. Prehistoric cultures of Northeast Angola and their signific https://doi.org/10.1017/S0003598X0010376X"
